Makerbot seems to be incapable of fixing the integrated openscad customizer. It's down for a long time now. You can still edit the design on your own computer. Download openscad and open the .scad file in the editor to modify the hub.

A customizable Clip that can be used for example to fix a spool on an axis.
Originally designed to be used with the customizable spool hub shown in the picture: (Springy Spool Hub) https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2334107

As this thing was constructed in openSCAD you can adapt it to your requirements in Customizer.

FAQ - What does "customizable" mean?

Customizable means that you can modify the model by changing the parameters that define it. In case of this thing you can modify for example the diameter of the rod, spring pretension etc. just by changing the respective numbers in the Customizer App.
The beautiful thing with parametric models is that you can adapt something to your needs without understanding the underlying design principles. Give it a try by clicking "Open in Customizer".

Update: I hope no-one already downloaded Version 4. Somehow a mistake snuck in through Sketchup, which I noticed after printing. Version 5 is now upgraded and fixed.

.......

This is a hardcase for a 3DConnexion 3D Mouse, some call it "the Puck".

I needed to create a case, that relieved the springs of the "puck" from being pushed and worn, when I take this mouse along on travels, in my backpack.

The case needs to be outfitted with 1mm thick foam on the inside, so that the mouse is held in there by pressure fit.(the yellow stuff in the photos, I didn't have one nice large piece, which would look much nicer). The case does not touch the "floating puck", it sits on the ring around the puck, which definitely needs the foam, so that the case does not scratch the plastic.

The 3D mouse is traction fit in there. Through the front hole, you can see the logo and it gives you access to simply pull the mouse out of the case. No bottom is needed to keep it simple, light and as small as possible.

Thoughts about the design and possible improvements

This is Version 5 of the design, but it is by no means perfect (I would have liked to have rounded over some of the sharp edges). Hopefully, the edge around the hole around the cable access isn't too short for the cable. Maybe someone can come up with a better solution around that, maybe even an integrated solution to wrap the cable around.

A little lip at the bottom on the inside may also give it a bit of a "click fit", but that's something that could be experimented with.

Hi, those who want to print this out please make sure you have your measurements before printing. Make sure you have scaled your hand as well. The scaling you use must be all the same for all 4 files.

Also as a reminder, this isn't a professional hand like the Flexy-Hand, Cyborg Beast, etc. made by professionals. I'm a student still learning the ways of 3D making and printing so please do not be agitated by the results when you printed it. Also, YOU HAVE BEEN WARNED.

What makes mine different from other 3D Prosthetic Hand is that you do not need the pins or other joints to connect fingers together or hand plate to wrist plate. Due to the small space of a 3D printer. I had to split them into 3 or 4 files to be printed in different parts. So after the hand is printed I would suggest getting a glue that can glue well on metal, wood, or plastic. *Note: I do not suggest to use hot glue. Then glue the parts together. However, if you have a bigger printer then I would suggest printing all parts of the hand together. Meaning each part is touching each other or attached to each other as one hand to be easier in the future. (Shown in pictures)

title: Drela AG24 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (34.74g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
This propeller was inspired and designed by using the Drela AG24 airfoil. Testing was done using the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Tester (test results provided below).

The part was printed with slow speed, with the help of a 0.2 nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The print was cleaned and deburred with the help of a Precision Knife

After this, I went on and sanded it with a piece of 400 grit sandpaper.

Here are the thrust readings for a few voltage values (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 14.55 grams
  • 2V => 21.96 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.9 grams
  • 3V => 34.74 grams

The files I included contain all pictures relevant to the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you want to have some fun with this propeller, you need to get a bunch of 8520 coreless motors.

You should use the SLDPRT extension files, should you desire to adapt the propeller model to suit your own needs.

Notice: The airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library for python.

description.text:
Update 08 March 2014 :
I received the roller, and I've been using them for two weeks now. The movements are very smooth, it seems to work fine. The printing quality is very good for me, see the pictures of the blue printed object (0.2mm layer).
Here a quick video : http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IDfdNB-six4&list=UU5Kj2JNFg6fteQoEoVRfevw&feature=share

Hi,
Just want to share a remix of the http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:215438 My motivation to find an alternative to the existing solutions is the cost. As electronhacks says in his blog, the Hiwin rails are really to expensive and the Dual 623 V rollers too (it reminds me that 3d.grabercars never answer me concerning the shipping cost, but anyway). I searched for days to find where buy those cheap rollers and I found on Ebay. Just search the words "roller" "shower" "bearing". The price is good for me : 4,50$ for two rollers, and there is a real bearing in it.
Here the dimensions of the roller :
Diameter of the wheel : 19mm
Width of the wheel : 5.5mm
Diameter of the screw : M6 My modifications :
  • You can tap the M3 hole to put a screw that can adjust the height of the printer (you don't touch the position of the endstop, just move down or up the M3 screw). It allows a very fine adjustment.
  • I reduced the thickness of the original endstop (2mm less) to align it with the M3 screw.
    • For the carriage for the GT2, I used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:121832 Don't hesitate to ask questions, and sorry for my english :-s

title: Flip-up front sight for RIS rail (Ver 0.1)

description.text:
An flip up sight, styled on the looks of the 
Magpul MBUS flip-up. Few things still to be 
developed (height adjustment, rear sight analog 
part, torsion spring), but should work just fine. 
As soon as i get the part from e-prototypy, i'll 
post some pics.

You'll need:
  • printed parts (duh)
  • 2x 2.5mm x 25mm steel pin
  • hexagon socket m3x30 screw
  • an ISO 4035 M3 nut
  • small rubber band
  • 10mm dia 10mm height coil spring
    • Assembly is quite simple. Attach the release to the bottom piece with the 2.5mm steel rod, put the large spring under it, press it down and attach the sight with the second rod. Last, place the rubber band into the notches on the side and bottom piece. To mount the sight on the rail, slide it on, put in place, insert the nut into the right side socket, then put the screw into the other-side hole, and screw in tightly.

This is my Genius Hour Presentation website. My project is an autonomous, electric, smart, transportation land vehicle. That got me thinking, what if we could take the human aspect of the driving. There are already made"smart cars" but these still rely on humans to drive them. Another thing that inspired me was a lego mindstorm which we program to drive around the game field, why couldn't we do that for a normal car. The last thing that inspired me was the bubbles from "Meet The Robinson" which is there form of an "autonomous transportation vehicle.

My vehicle is a smart vehicle taxi/tram type system. It use radio waves to signal between one another allowing a total autonomous vehicle. It is a small interlocking, and adjustable. description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/j5DfkwAXhOa

Split 1x2x3

Ok, Ryan, you win. I like "split 1x2x3" a lot better than "1x2x3 2x2x3 mashup", but it's not like it was YOUR idea to name it "split" anyways! >:(

Anyhow, this is my 1x2x3 with sliding caps and center supports. Also, I invented this puzzle so your technically downloading the original even though I uploaded this design way after Ryan. Support the designers! If you haven't yet played with this puzzle it's moderately hard, unlike its 1x2x3 counterpart, and is actually slightly fun to solve. It also looks crazy bad when scrambled. Go ahead! Print away!

Print:

  • 1 x Center-1
  • 1 x Center-2
  • 4 x Corner-1
  • 4 x Corner-2
  • 2 x Cap

Assembly

First, slide all the corner pieces into the centers like you would on a 1x2x3. To assemble the cores you will need one M3 screw and nut as well as a spring. Put the nut in the center with the hexagonal hole. Put the spring on the screw and put it through the other centerpiece. Screw the screw in the nut. :l rather simple. Slide the two caps in and apply stickers to secure them in place. And that's it, folks!

Disclaimer

This puzzle is built with zero tolerance meaning that there is no space between the pieces. You will probably need to do a little sanding to get the pieces just right.

I've always loved the driptip that came with my Stingray X (RIP, less than a week old, TSA killed it when they rooted through my bag and dropped it. Skipped 4 threads on the lock ring). I've rebuilt it here with some improvements and wider funneling (seen in the cut away). Double O-Ring (Standard size?).

It's simple but very comfortable and nice. I recommend printing with a thick wall and heavy infill, or use Proto-Pasta Stainless Steel for authentic results.

Many electronic items we make here have tiny little sliding switches for power etc. These are difficult to use with big clumsy fingers and generally when a device is packaged you need to poke a needle or paper clip through a tiny hole in the side near the switch or something similarly inconvenient to activate the switch. Or at least that is how it was until now...
This is a simple parametric part that allows you to activate a switch. It can be made fit into a gap between a PCB and an enclosure with it's nub poking through the side of the casing and a slot on the rear catching the much smaller nub of e.g. a small surface mount switch. There should be enough clearance between all sides on the pcb and enclosure for it run reasonably smoothly, also ensure there is enough room at the ends to allow the switch the move along its full length of travel!
I've used it in several enclosures and devices to make it easier to turn things on and off.
See the picture for an example (the switch catch is the dark grey part)

• Design electronics and enclosure with a little bit of room for this item near the switch
  • Measure the size of your switch nub and it's travel
  • Mount PCB into packaging and measure clearance on all sides near switch
  • Plug values into parametric script and make .stl
  • Print, cleanup and install switch
  • Easily turn things on-off

I did not design this, wild bill from benbox laser forums has full credit for this one..

I have not made this either, I have the newer machine with the aluminium mount, scad file included if you need to make changes.

title: Drela AG25 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (33.83g thrust @3V)

description.text:
The propeller was inspired and designed by using the Drela AG25 airfoil. All testing was done on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Tester You can inspect the results below.

Part printed at slow speed, with a 0.2 nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The print was cleaned with an X-ACTO Knife

After this, I then got to finish the propeller with a small piece of 500 grit sandpaper.

These are the measurements for a few voltage presets (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 12.34 grams
  • 2V => 21.25 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.33 grams
  • 3V => 33.83 grams

The files you can download consist of all the pictures taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you'd like to tinker with this propeller, you should get a few 8520 coreless motors.

Use the SLDPRT files, just in case you desire to adapt the model to suit your needs.

Notice: The airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library for python.

title: Drela AG26 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (35.16g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
I created this drone propeller by using the Drela AG26 airfoil. Testing was done using the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (test results provided below).

The part was printed with slow speed, with the help of a 0.2mm nozzle at 0.04 layer height. The final part was cleaned with the help of a Precision Knife

After this, I went on and sanded it with a 400 grit sandpaper.

These are the thrust measurements for a few voltage values (you can also check these out in the images):

  • 1.5V => 11.59 grams
  • 2V => 20.95 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.6 grams
  • 3V => 35.16 grams

The files I included contain all pictures relevant to the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the printable STL files and the SLDPRT files. Should you want to play with the propeller, make sure you have a couple of 8520 coreless motors.

Use the SLDPRT files, just in case you wish to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Notes: Airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library in python.

title: Prusa i3 dual extruder cyclops hotend

description.text:
This is my version of a dual color/extrusion prusa i3 with a cyclops hotend (single nozzle).

That printer was for some people who want to use pla+hips as support material (yeah I know that is not a good combo...).
But after some (a lot...) test I was able to print "correctly" PLA+hips.
The cyclops hotend is not the best hotend for PLA... I have to use a very short retraction (only 3mm) to prevent continous jamming...
While for the hips I could use retraction up to 9mm. Printing temperature was 210° (so it could print PLA and HIPS without changing temperature), and 65° for the bed.
As I said PLA+HIPS is not the best combo... the 2 materials are really different...
But as you can see it could work.

If you want to download the file visit my website at the link below ;)
http://www.indiegearlab.com/prusa-i3-cyclops-hotend-files/3664

title: Expanding helping objects on printing surface

description.text:
idea is really simple: you need several things which not many 3d printing softwares can do: you need measuring ruler in all 3 dimensions, you need simple objects without 3d modeling, you need helping hands on 3d printing surface.
All you need is this package which will surely grow during time. If you have any new idea, feel free to share in comments.
This pack contains:
simple cube 1x1x1mm- idea is that, when you need precise measurement on printing table that you expand (scale) that cube in proportion which will help you measure that. For instance, when you need to measure 26,5mm into Z axis, you expand cube on number 26,5 into z, so you will know how tall something is
simple roller 1x1x1mm- does the same thing, but its a roller, you can measure diameter of stuff with this
empty cone- imagine if you need to support some really tall and thin object, to not fall from printing surface, but you cannot turn on support because it will support stuff which is not supposed to support. than you use this empty cone, put on a printing surface over that rod for example and slice it with it. It will give you support and it will not poison other parts with support (look at picture)
So, idea is really simple, give it a try, if you are printing anything, you need excatly how tall, thick, angled (use some simple equasion) something is, so use theese simple tool for achiving best printing resoult.
Knowledge is power! Happy printing! :)
